HEADWORD: Depreciation
<hw>De*pre`ci*a"tion</hw>
<pr>(d⟦esl⟧*pr⟦emac⟧`sh⟦icr⟧*⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧pr⟦eacute⟧ciation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of lessening, or seeking to lessen, price, value, or
reputation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The falling of value; reduction of worth.</def>
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>the state of being depreciated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Depreciative</ent>⟦br⟧
